Attributions

- The `orchestration/cn-plugin/` plugin architecture (commands, agents,
  skills, companion scripts) is derived from and inspired by
  openai/codex-plugin-cc (https://github.com/openai/codex-plugin-cc),
  the Codex plugin for Claude Code by OpenAI, licensed under Apache-2.0.

- The Phase 5 "Review-Fix Loop" design in `orchestration/fanout/SKILL.md`
  draws on published work on agentic verification loops:
    - Tim Williams, "LLM Verification Loops: Best Practices and Patterns"
    - "Loop Engineering: Why the Best AI Agents in 2026 Are Built as Loops"
    - Reflexion / Self-Refine (academic literature)

- The `Workspace isolation` and `Experience memory` concepts in
  `orchestration/fanout/` are inspired by Zleap-AI/Zleap-Agent
  (https://github.com/Zleap-AI/Zleap-Agent) — concepts only; the code is
  an independent implementation, as Zleap ships without a license.

- The loop's auto-fix vs ask-user finding split, the `fanout run` state
  facade, and the `check-docs` docs-match-code drift gate are inspired by
  kunchenguid/no-mistakes (https://github.com/kunchenguid/no-mistakes) and
  lavish-axi (https://github.com/kunchenguid/lavish-axi), licensed MIT —
  ideas only; the implementations here are independent.

- The orchestrator-side ownership / violation-detection idea behind
  `fanout integrate --ownership` is inspired by merkyor/Lynn
  (https://gitee.com/merkyor/Lynn).

- `fanout skills forge` delegates skill authoring to Anthropic's official
  `skill-creator` Claude Code meta-skill, and the `fanout skills validate`
  gate mirrors the checks in its `quick_validate.py`.

- The adaptive router (`fanout allocate`) draws on the multi-armed-bandit
  literature: Thompson Sampling (Agrawal & Goyal, 2012) and
  non-stationary / discounted bandits (Garivier & Moulines, 2011).
